Organs that have mesothelial lining-have visceral (forms surface of organ, inner layer) and parietal (covers abdominal)layers.

What are the primary retroperitoneal organs?

Aorta, IVC, kidneys and ureters, suprarenal glands
LOB 1
What are the secondary retroperitoneal organs?

parts 2-4 of the duodenum, pancreas, ascending and descending colon
LOB 1

The foregut contains the {{c1::esophagus,}} {{c2::stomach,}} {{c3::duodenum}} (1st half), {{c4::liver,}} {{c5::gallbladder,}} {{c6::pancreas}} and {{c7::spleen}}
SLO 3

The midgut contains the {{c1::dudoenum}} (2nd half), {{c2::jejunum,}} {{c3::the ileum,}} {{c4::cecum,}} {{c5::appendix,}} {{c6::ascending colon,}} and {{c7::transverse colon}} (proximal 2/3)
SLO 3
The hindgut contains the {{c1::transverse colon}} (distal 1/3), {{c2::descending colon,}} {{c3::sigmoid colon}} and {{c4::rectum}}
The abdominal esophagus passes through the {{c1::respiratory diaphragm}} roughly at {{c2::T12}}
What is the superior anchoring point of the sotmach?
What is the inferior anchoring point of the stomach?
Where are the pancreas relative to the stomach?
What does the splenic artery look like?
The gastrocolic ligament is largely covered by the {{c1::greater omentum}}
The {{c2::duodenum}} wraps around the head of the {{c1::pancreas}}
The duodenum is next to the {{c1::right}} kidney
The {{c1::circular folds}} of the duodenum are clinically relevant to the {{c2::barium swallow}}
The head of the pancreas is encircled by the {{c1::2nd part}} of the duodenum
The {{c1::body of the}} pancreas is retroperitoneal
The {{c1::tail}} of the pancreas is anterior to the peritoneum, sometimes near the {{c2::spleen}}
The duodenum and the pancreas are {{c1::anterior}} to the renal veins
The portal vein is {{c1::posterior}} to the neck of the pancreas, and is the {{c2::last line}} that drains the {{c3::gut}} into the {{c4::liver}} to be filtered
The portal vein is formed by the junction of the {{c1::superior mesenteric}} vein and {{c2::inferior mesenteric}} vein
The caudate/quadratic lobe is anatomically part of the {{c1::right}} lobe of the liver, but functionally are part of the {{c2::left}} liver
The caudate lobe of the liver is more {{c1::posterior,}} while the quadrate lobe is more {{c2::anterior}}
The jejunum tends to be more {{c1::jagged}} in lumen and more {{c2::proximal}}, while the illeum tends to be {{c3::smoother}} and more {{c4::distal}}
The vasa recta of the jejunum are {{c1::long}} and {{c2::few,}} while they are {{c3::shorter}} and {{c4::more numerous}} in the ileum
The small intestine is composed of the {{c3::duodenum}}, {{c2::jejunum}} and {{c1::ileum}} and covered by {{c4::mesentery}}
What are the symptoms of patients with appendicitis?
N/V, fever beginning after pain starts, pain starting at umbilicus (T10), pain at R lower abdomen by 24 hours
The hindgut contains the {{c1::second third}} of the transverse colon
What are the 3 different venous drainages of the rectum and anal canal?
Superior rectal, middle rectal, and inferior rectal.
What is an example of portal/caval anastamosis?
The middle rectal vein draining to common illiac
What are the 4 vsins of the hepatic portal system?
Portal vein, splenic vein, superior mesenteric vein, inferior mesenteric vein
What happens to blood if the liver is no longer functional?
The blood backs up through anastamoses, and blood dries to get into caval systems
What happens in hepatic hypertension via porto-caval anastaomsis?
Fetal patent opens through hypertension; inferior epigastric v and superficial epigastric vein back up and flow through umbilicla portal to para umbilical vein

The azygos vein is a vein running up the {{c1::right side}} of the thoracic vertebral column draining itself towards the {{c2::superior vena cava.}} It connects the systems of {{c3::superior vena cava}} and {{c4::inferior vena cava}} and can provide an alternative path for blood to the {{c5::right atrium}} when either of the {{c6::venae cavae}} is blocked.
If a patient has a problem with the pancreas, putting pressure on the SMA, what vessel could be affected?
The left renal vein could be choked off
If a patient has bleeding in the anterior abdominal wall, what vessels are likely affected?
Superior and inferior epigastric arteries (and possibly internal branch of internal thoracic artery, which branches into superior epigastric artery and musculophrenic artery)
What is the first portion of the duodenum?
First part=superior part, of the duodenum is a continuation from the pylorus to transpyloric plane. It is superior to the rest of the segments, at the vertebral level of L1.
What is the second part of the duodenum?

The second part, or descending part, of the duodenum begins at the superior duodenal flexure. It goes inferior to the lower border of vertebral body L3. Head of pancreas encircled by 2nd part of duodenum

The third part, or horizontal part or inferior part of the duodenum begins at the inferior duodenal flexure and passes transversely to the left, passing in front of the inferior vena cava, abdominal aorta and the vertebral column.

The fourth part, or ascending part, of the duodenum passes upward, joining with the jejunum at the duodenojejunal flexure. The fourth part of the duodenum is at the vertebral level L3, and may pass directly on top, or slightly to the left, of the aorta
The tail of the pancreas is {{c1::peritoneal}}
What are the posterior wall nerves, and what are their dermatomes?
Subcostal nerve (T12) and illohypogastric/inguinal (L1), which ends at hypogastric region
when the small intesting is flipped to the {{c1::left,}} the {{c2::root of mesentery}} bordering {{c3::RT infracolic}} compartment is visible
The descending colon ends in the {{c1::sigmoid colon}}
The rectum has {{c1::transverse}} folds, the SI has {{c2::full circular}} folds, and the LI has {{c3::semiciruclar}} folds
Teniae coli form {{c1::complete longitudinal muscle coat}} at rectum
The celiac trunk divides into SMA at {{c1::LV1,}} and IMA at {{c2::LV3}}
Where does the abdominal aorta pass through the respiratory diaphragm?
Where does the IVC pass through the diaphragm?
The celiac trunk divides into the l{{c1::}}eft gastric artery, {{c2::splenic artery,}} and {{c3::common hepatic artery}}
Where does the left gastric artery supply blood to?
Where does the common hepatic supply blood to?
goes to the right, liver or duodenum to juncion with arteries

The branches of the left colic artery anastomose with branches of the {{c1::middle colic}} and {{c2::sigmoid}} arteries and contribute to the formation of the{{c3:: marginal artery of Drummond, }}an arterial channel that supplies the{{c4:: large intestine.}}

The normal "pi" of the hepatic portal system: main portal vein is formed by the {{c1::splenic vein}} and the {{c2::superior mesenteric vein. }} The splenic veins drains to the {{c3::portal vein}} which drains to the {{c4::liver. }} The {{c7::SMV}} drains to the {{c8::portal vein}} which drains to the {{c9::liver.}}
The distal esophagus and {{c1::right}} and {{c2::left gastric veins}} drain directly into the {{c3::portal vein,}} which is an example of {{c4::portal veinal anastamosis}}
Parts II and III of the duodenum are {{c1::retroperitoneal}} and {{c2::medial}} to ascending colon

The duodenum is anterior to the {{c1::IVC}} and {{c2::abdominal aorta}}
SLO 4
The superior mesenteric artery comes across {{c1::1/3}} of the {{c2::duodenum}}
The portal vein is located right where {{c1::the neck of the pancreas}} crosses midline.
The {{c1::portal vein}} accepts all blood from the {{c2::abdominal viscera}}, which is then sent to the liver for filtering.
Symptoms of appendicisit include {{c1::umbilical pain}} first, followed by {{c2::nausea, vomiting and fever}}, followed by {{c3::pain at right lower abdomen by 24 hours.}}
Umbilical pain in appendicitis is causde by {{c1::visceral afferent sympathetics}} sending referred pain to the level of {{c2::T10}}
Caput medusa is caused by porto-caval anastamoses in the {{c1::portal-umbilical vein}}

Esophageal varices are {{c1::abnormal, enlarged veins}} in the esophagus that occur because of {{c2::portal vein obstruction (usually liver disease)}}. Blood backs up through the esophagus and tries to go into the {{c3::azygous vein.}}
SLO 8
